    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-07-02T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-07-02T06:00:00-05:00" n="112"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/8–250: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Deputy Representative on the North Atlantic
                        Council</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spofford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-02T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 2, 1950—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Depto1">Depto</gloss> 30. Fifth session <gloss
                        target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> deputies considered Standing Group’s
                        report<note n="1" xml:id="d112fn1">See footnote 1, <ref target="#pg_162">p.
                            162</ref>.</note> and heard <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss>
                    presentation covering following points: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>What <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> has done so far: <list>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Development medium term defense plan which now being revised
                                    and refined by regional groups.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Study of short term defense plan, for which regional plans due
                                    September 1.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Revised state of defense preparedness of which main
                                    deficiencies are lack of trained personnel, of equipment, of
                                    infrastructure and effective reserve formations.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>What <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> proposes to do to improve state
                            of preparedness. <list>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                                <item>More detailed guidance on collective balance of forces.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Guidance on standardization of weapons and equipment and on
                                    structure of forces.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Analysis of differences of mobilization procedures.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Improve and coordinate training arrangements.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">e</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Recommend establishment of stockpiles.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">f</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Consider reorganization of regions for greater
                                    efficiency.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>What <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> considers <gloss
                                target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> deputies could do to improve state of
                            preparedness. <list>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Direct immediate national action towards increasing total
                                    effective combat forces (<gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss>
                                    considers there is no reason wait for more detailed studies,
                                    that anything done now will be in right direction, that
                                    energetic start needed now and that previous unsuccessful
                                    efforts of military authorities and defense ministers to get
                                    increases must now be strongly backed by deputies).</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Obtain governmental approval for executive power to enforce
                                    agreed resolutions in name of Council.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Assume deputies now concerned with getting agreements on
                                    equitable distribution of national defense efforts to provide
                                    necessary forces.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Improve scope of national military service.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">e</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Recommended to governments an initial program for high
                                    priority military production in Europe.</item>
                                <label>
                                    <hi rend="italic">f</hi>.</label>
                                <item>Coordinate work of Defense Committee, <gloss target="#t_DFEC1"
                                        >DFEC</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_MPSB1"
                                    >MPSB</gloss>.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Discussion of need for coordination of Standing Group with <gloss
                                target="#t_DFEC1">DFEC</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_MPSB1"
                                >MPSB</gloss> to question on <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss>
                            guidance as to types and volume of high priority equipment of which
                            production should be started immediately. Tedder<note n="2"
                                xml:id="d112fn2">Marshal of the Royal Air Force Lord Tedder, British
                                Representative on the Standing Group.</note> stated as <gloss
                                target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> opinion that <gloss target="#t_MPSB1"
                                >MPSB</gloss> knows enough <pb facs="0199" n="177" xml:id="pg_177"/>
                            of immediate production capabilities and requirements for high priority
                            items to consider immediate production increases. <gloss target="#t_SG1"
                                >SG</gloss> listed six general categories of equipment that should
                            be given urgent priority: tactical aircrafts, anti-aircraft equipment,
                            including radar; anti-tank weapons; tanks; mine weapons and escort
                            vessels; field artillery. Ely<note n="3" xml:id="d112fn3">Lt. Gen. Paul
                                Ely, French Representative on the Standing Group.</note> stated that
                                <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> realized military guidance needed
                            both as to volume and type equipment needing high priority production
                            but stated that decision on types could only be worked out in
                            consultation with <gloss target="#t_MPSB1">MPSB</gloss>. Suggested
                            immediately sending rep to Washington to work on the problem.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Statement on new weapons aroused considerable interest (being
                                pouched).<note n="4" xml:id="d112fn4">Not printed.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>One subject on which discussion centered was <gloss target="#t_SG1"
                                >SG</gloss> guidance on concept of balance collective forces.
                            Crittenberger stated <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> has draft of
                            further guidance on this subject on which agreement is expected within
                            few days. <gloss target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> paper includes statement of
                            principles, covers four stages by which balancing will be achieved and
                            assigns certain tasks to regions. Tedder explained <gloss
                                target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> assigns primary tasks to nations and
                            regional groups expected to recommend adjustment of national forces to
                            meet assigned task. Alphand questioned desirability of relying on
                            separate national actions which might not be coordinated with plans of
                            other nations. Tedder affirmed confidence in ability of each nation to
                            “face up to facts” and stated each nation, knowing its primary assigned
                            task, can decide whether it is devoting too much effort to other tasks
                            and should change emphasis.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>Deputies agreed issue press release stating that <gloss
                                target="#t_SG1">SG</gloss> representatives had met with deputies to
                            discuss defense matters.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Department <gloss target="#t_Depto1">Depto</gloss> 30, repeated info Paris
                    183 pass <gloss target="#t_OSR1">OSR</gloss>, Hague 31, Brussels 30, Copenhagen
                    22, Oslo 16, Ottawa 9, Lisbon 14, Rome 43, Frankfort unnumbered pass Heidelberg
                    for Handy. Department pass Secretary of Defense.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>[<hi rend="smallcaps">Spofford</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
